<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Plagiobothrys</i> <i>nothofulvus</i> is characteristically present or dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Amsinckia</i> <i>menziesii</i>, <i>Avena</i> spp., <i>Bromus</i> spp., <i>Calochortus</i> <i>luteus</i>, <i>Castilleja</i> <i>attenuata</i>, <i>Castilleja</i> <i>exserta</i>, <i>Clarkia</i> spp., <i>Daucus</i> <i>pusillus</i>, <i>Dichelostemma</i> <i>capitatum</i>, <i>Erodium</i> spp., <i>Eschscholzia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Eschscholzia</i> <i>lobbii</i>, <i>Holocarpha</i> <i>virgata</i>, <i>Hordeum</i> <i>murinum</i>, <i>Lasthenia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Lotus</i> spp., <i>Lupinus</i> spp., <i>Phacelia</i> <i>ramosissima</i>, <i>Plagiobothrys</i> <i>collinus</i>, <i>Plagiobothrys</i> <i>fulvus</i> and <i>Trifolium</i> spp. Emergent shrubs may be present at low cover. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Plagiobothrys nothofulvus</i> > 1% absolute cover in the herbaceous layer; <i>Bromus</i> spp. may dominate, but stands always include <i>P. nothofulvus</i> (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Upland slopes. Soils are loamy, derived from many substrates, and often subject to high levels of bioturbation. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Plagiobothrys nothofulvus</i> as a FAC plant. </div>
</div>

        
