<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Fires in annual grasslands occur at low intensity, with little heat transported more than a few centimeters into the soil; seeds in the soil are generally unaffected. Native Americans used fire very frequently in grasslands and oak savannas (Anderson 2005), where they tended patches of <i>Plagiobothrys </i>and many other herbs with edible seeds. The fires were set to increase vigor and numbers of these seed-banking species in the following spring via nutrient release (Menke and Rice 1981) and concomitant thatch removal. Lightning is infrequent and insufficient to maintain herbaceous openings in woodlands, and woody plants may colonize openings without disturbance (Reiner 2007, Tyler et al. 2007).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
