    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Plagiobothrys nothofulvus</i> includes the Mojave Desert (322A), Southern California Coast (261B), and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa, Ac-d, Aj-l). Stands appear commonly in openings in oak woodlands and in disturbed settings such as grazed pastures and recent burns in the inland potion of the Santa Lucia Range.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-f, Ah, Aj). Stands develop frequently in rolling grasslands, openings in oak woodlands, and disturbed settings as at Wagon Caves cRNA (Keeler-Wolf 1989b, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ab, Ae, Ag, An-o). Stands in Merced Co. occur with <i>Bromus</i> spp. on loamy upland soils adjacent vernal pool habitats. Stands have been observed in the Sutter Buttes and along the base of the coast ranges.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). Stands seasonally exist on hills throughout the section, closely associated with stands of the <i>Quercus douglasii</i> alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Stands often carpet hillsides in the early spring (Klein et al. 2007). Stands generally favor moderate slopes below 400 m adjacent to <i>Q. douglasii</i> woodlands and other herbaceous alliances. <i>Bromus hordeaceus</i> and <i>Trifolium hirtum</i> typically have average higher cover values than does <i>P. nothofulvus.</i> Other stands sampled near Yosemite National Park, identified as <i>Trifolium microcephalum-Daucus pusillus- Bromus hordeaceus</i> association (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), appear similar to these stands.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Managers are unclear as to the proper management balance for emphasizing <i>Plagiobothrys nothofulvus </i>rather than non-natives. Schiffman (2007) suggested that the non-native <i>Erodium </i>spp. have very similar ecologies to the native annual herbs; the non-natives are regularly in competition with the natives. The non-native bromes attain strong dominance in years of high rainfall (Bartolome et al. 2007a). 

Anderson (2005) discussed Native American use of the seeds of <i>P. nothofulvus </i>and other herbs for food. Stands were enhanced historically as a result of their management. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
